title: For Sale:  MAS Model 1936/51 - 7.5 French, 95%+ Condition
postcontent:
This is a much less frequently seen MAS Model 1936/51 rifle. 

It's essentially a Model 1936 that has been strengthened to accommodate the built in grenade launching system. 

This rifle is finished differently than most of the 36's and 49/56's you'll see. The wood has a smoother and more glossy finish while the metal has a much darker almost black look. Most of the MAS rifles I've seen sport a medium gray finish. I suspect it is a black phosphate type coating, or perhaps a matte bluing, because it does not appear to be paint. 

Overall condition is at least 95% with only the most minor handling and storage marks. The bore is mirror bright and the rifle may be unfired. 

The numbers on the receiver, bolt, magazine floor plate and buttstock match. 

The sling is original in tan colored leather and it's in excellent condition. 

The needle style bayonet that stores inside the lower handguard has the same dark finish and is excellent. 

The black slip on recoil pad is marked MAS 51 and the rubber is soft and pliable with no cracking or hardening at all. 

Rifle inclusdes three boxes of clean brass case surplus ammo which is probably corrosive primed so be sure to clean after firing. 

Price is $600 with pickup in the Brandon area. Buyer must be a Florida resident and at least 18 to purchase. 

Thanks for looking.

postcontent:
This is a CZ 52 pistol that I bought nearly 25 years ago. It's quite unusual as it has both a 7.62 x 25, and a 9mm Luger barrel that have matching numbers from the factory. 

I've done a good deal of research and there isn't much info available on this pistol. I can only find one other on-line example with the matching barrels and it sold on GunBroker about a year ago. It did have factory matching barrels but the entire forward portion of the left side of the slide was stamped with a very large and unsightly import mark. The pistol for sale today has an import mark, but it's so small and lightly struck that I need a strong magnifying glass to see it. Pistol is unfired and it's as close to 100% condition you are likely to get. 

Grips & metal finishes are nearly perfect and the bore in both barrels is pristine. All numbers match. The holster, lanyard and three of the four magazines I purchased with the pistol are still in their original sealed factory packaging.

7.62 x 25 & 9mm Luger barrels - numbers factory matched to pistol

title: For Sale:  Leupold Mark 4 LR/T (Taking Offers)
postcontent:
This 3.5-10x40 is the optic that the military uses on many of the MK12 Special Purpose Rifles (SPR). It is also the same optic that Marcus Luttrell was using during the 'Lone Survivor' event where he and a few other brave SEALs fought hundreds of Afghan a**holes. 

The scope is in excellent condition with only the edges of the turrets shined a bit (barely noticeable) due to living and traveling in a soft case. It features an illuminated Tactical Milling Reticle that can be used as a ballistic reticle. It has been converted to .5 MOA adjustments from the Leupold custom shop and has a custom BDC turret that is calibrated to a 77 grain bullet at 2850 feet per second (determine the range and turn the elevation turret to the corresponding number). I have tested the BDC turret extensively and it is true to 600 yards which was the longest shot I could take until I recently secured a place with just over 1000 meters. Additionally, I have turrets for 62 grain 5.56, 168 grain 7.62, and the standard MOA turret.

The mount is a LaRue QD SPR mount that is also in very good condition. I have also tested the return to zero quality of this mount extensively and have never experienced a discernable shift even at 600 yards. LaRue claims that it will return to 1/10 of a MOA and after owning several of these mounts I know for a fact it is that good or better.

I am now shooting larger cartridges at greater distances and need more magnification. I'm going to have to sacrifice this Leupold to fund the high end optic for this application. After the work from the custom shop I have over $1700 in this optic and mount. I am open to offers but lowball offers will not get a response, don't waste your time. This is a face to face sale only in the North Alabama area, I will not ship. For the most part I'm interested in cash, however, I may consider a trade for ARs, AR uppers, or high end optics if something is offered that would compel me to sell something else.

title: For Sale:  700 yd AR-- Custom built
postcontent:
I have decided to sell my custom AR "sniper" rifle because I'm going bigger and farther and have other AR's. You read correctly this gun has made a 700 yd (640 M) shot on a hog and missed the target point by 3/8" with a 7mph wind on 72 grain loads. This rifle has a 24" stainless heavy duty barrel with a 1:8 twist that was built by a gunsmith who builds custom competition rifles in North Carolina, so this guy knows about long range shooting. The only way I was able to get this upper was by my affiliation with some Marine Snipers and I don't think I could get another one. It is sitting on a Spikes lower with a Wilson tactical trigger assembly. It has a magpul custom grip and buttstock with storage, an adjustable bi-pod that allows you to swivel while set, and a Nikon 3-12 X 40 1/4 MOA scope. It has a Black Dawn BCG and charge handle for smooth long lasting use. I have only put about 80 rounds through this rifle and hunted it once and has a 100% take down record. The rifle is capable of 600+yd shots with extreme accuracy and can handle heavier loads than standard AR's. The rifle is most fun at a range of about 3-400yds and is extremely accurate and effective, not to mention just fun to shoot. I love the rifle, but I have decided to go 338 and it's gonna cost a lot of $$$ to get there. I'm not really interested in trading, except for maybe a SCAR or an FNAR 308, Savage and Remington 700's or certain pistols ( Springfield, S&W, FNH or certain Glocks ) but will entertain any offers. If you would like to contact the Marine who built this I would gladly make that possible, I have nothing to hide and he will confirm that this is a fantastic rifle on a platform that is both accurate and affordable to operate. I will gladly demo this rifle at a nearby range, it's a short range but a range nonetheless, but bring your own ammo.  The upper alone cost almost $1500, if you can find a shelf unit like this they range from $12-1800, and I am asking $2150 OBO for the entire rifle with a case a two mags. If I don't sell it I won't be upset, it's a great rifle to shoot and hunt with and I really enjoy its capabilities and accuracy.  
 If you want to know what it cost to build this rifle just go find all of the components, if they're available, and add it up, then you will see why I'm asking what I'm asking. Not trying to be a jerk, it's just the facts, this a very unique rifle that I don't think I could even reproduce at a reasonable cost, especially not the upper. 
 There is NOTHING stock about this rifle and you can tell when you shoot it, very smooth, very accurate and extremely reliable, never a FTF or FTE, EVER!

If you have any questions just call    210-25 nine- thirty 20

title: For Sale:  Colt SAA 1st Gen.2 Gun Set 45 7.5" Eagle Ivorys       EARLY PRODUCTION 1876-77 Orig.Finish Blue/Patina
postcontent: This set of Colt SAA Revolvers is a Beautiful Pair of Original Condition Guns that belong to a close friend who is a prominent businessman and well known gun collector in the KC area since the early 1960's. He is making these guns available due to his age and not a need to sell. He has a vast collection of fine firearms and has decided to reduce the size of his collection in some areas such as this set of Colt Single Action Army Revolvers. The description of the guns is as follows: Gun number one is a Colt SAA Blue finish with a 7 1/2 inch barrel in 45 LC and was made in 1876 and shipped to H & D Folsom Arms Co. in Georgia on Dec.30, 1876. The number of guns in this shipment was 50, which tells me this gun was not a special order gun because of the number of guns in the shipment. The gun however does have a custom set of Eagle/Snake carved Ivory grips, carvings on the left grip that are nicely aged to this gun they are fit so well. I believe Colt did this set along with the same exact style carved grip on right grip of gun number two. This gun is in excellent shape. Also the cylinder is matching. The lockup on the cylinder is amazingly tight for a gun this old and it still has the four clicks when cocking hammer. The gun, as most Colts of this age, is a nice even wear Patina/Blue finish with the blue about 40% that has not had steel wool or sand paper rubbed all over it. The screws are all in good shape. The cylinder pin screw does show wear. The bore is somewhat dark but excellent for a gun of this age. The Carved Ivory Grips are outstanding on both guns. Gun number two is in as good or better condition than the first gun. This gun is also a Colt SAA Blue finish with a 7 1/2 inch barrel in 45 LC Serial number 40885, made one year later than gun one. We do not have the Colt letter to this gun but if important one can be obtained. The gun does have matching serial numbers on the frame, trigger guard, grip frame, and cylinder. The lockup on the cylinder is tight and again it has the familiar Colt sound of four distinctive clicks when cocking the hammer. This gun,as the first gun, is a very nice even patina finish with slightly more percentage blue finish left on barrel, that has not been messed with and is ALL ORIGINAL as is gun number one. The screws are excellent except again the cylinder pin screw does show wear. The bore is also the same condition as the first gun.As always even with the guns in tight condition shooting modern ammo is not a good idea we are selling this set as a collectable not shooters. The Carved Ivory Grips are as nice a pair of carved ivorys as you will find if you like time period ivory instead of brand new ivory. These two guns were purchased as a set by my friend in 1975 and in my opinion the original person who purchased these guns over 130 years ago had Colt install these Ivory grips at the same time or very close to the same time. I say this because the grips are exact in every way and show the same amount of aging, as do the guns and it would make sense to have one right panel and one left panel carved so they would be a right and left hand set...
